Determinant

The origin of the determinant can be found in trying to solve Linear Systems of Equations.
It turns out that the unknowns of a solution can be calculated using a determinant more specifically with Cramer's Rule.

Definition

The idea of the determinant of an matrix can be derived from the method of substitution.
Recall from Cramer's Rule that the solution to any unknown takes a form such that the denominator of the unknown is the determinant of the coefficient matrix. Thus, if the determinant is , then the system has no solution.

From this formula of the determinant, we can see some interesting properties of the determinant.

  1. Each term is a product of elements from different rows and columns. ie: no two elements in a term share a row or column.
  2. The sign of the determinant can be visualized as a slope. This is best visualized with Sarrus' Rule.

We can choose to let the permutation modify the row of the entry instead of the column. This won't change the output because both describe the same thing, ie: all possible products of entries from different rows and columns.

Geometric Interpretation

A scalar that describes the factor in which area (space) changes for a given transformation (from standard coordinates ).

eg: scales by a factor of .

By definition of a linear transformation, the factor by which the bases are scaled after a transformation (determinant) is the same factor for all other vectors in the vector space.

Fact: the determinant is if it condenses all points in a dimensional space into a dimensional space where .

  • For a x matrix, the unsigned determinant represents the area of the parallelogram formed by the column vectors that make up the matrix.
  • For a x matrix, the unsigned determinant is the volume of the parallelepiped formed by the bases of the matrix.
  • And so on.

Negative Determinant in 2D

In the right hand orientation, is to the left hand of . If a transformation results in being to the right hand of , then we say that the transformation inverses the orientation. Whenever orientation is flipped, the determinant is negative.
eg: flips orientation because corresponds to and corresponds to which is to the right of when it was originally to the left.

Negative Determinant in 3D


The right hand rule is a useful mnemonic for remembering a right-handed orientation. It is convention to have a right-handed orientation be the standard orientation. In that case, right-handed bases represent a positive determinant and left-handed bases, negative.

eg: if we choose that a right-hand orientation be positive, then the identity has the property that the smallest angle between and is counter-clockwise.
If we wanted a left-handed orientation to be positive,
the standard bases have the property that the smallest angle between and is clockwise. (there is the left-hand rule for visualizing this one).

If reverses orientation, ie: from right to left, or left to right, then the determinant will be negative.
